{"id":"993623434187891459","name":"Nargile Hookah Shisha","lastUpdateDate":"2021-07-06T16:53:56.420Z","publisherHandle":"nikolaevadinara","publisherImage":"https://s3-alpha.figma.com/profile/79fa4ea8-b788-415f-a9db-09e1906494b9","publisherId":"3889642","publisherName":"Dinara Nikolaeva","thumbnailUrl":"https://s3-alpha.figma.com/hub/file/962453417/1175e494-83c8-4416-ac80-f6c10692a9fd-cover.png","description":"<p>A <strong>hookah</strong> (<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindustani_language\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Hindustani</a>: حقّہ(<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nastaleeq\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Nastaleeq</a>), हुक़्क़ा(<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Devanagari\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Devanagari</a>), IPA: <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA/Hindi_and_Urdu\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">[ˈɦʊqːa]</a>; also see <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hookah#Names_and_etymology\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">other names</a>),<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hookah#cite_note-TCALR1916-1\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">[1]</a><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hookah#cite_note-1994Pathak-2\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">[2]</a> or <strong>shisha</strong>, is a single- or multi-stemmed instrument for <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heating\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">heating</a> or <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vaporizing\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">vaporizing</a> and then <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smoking\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">smoking</a> either <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tobacco\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">tobacco</a>, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flavored_tobacco\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">flavored tobacco</a> (often <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mu%E2%80%98assel\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Mu‘assel</em></a>), or sometimes <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cannabis_(drug)\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">cannabis</a>, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hashish\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">hashish</a>, and in the past <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Opium\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">opium</a>. The smoke is passed through a water basin—often glass-based—before inhalation.</p><p>There are two theories regarding the origin of hookah. The first is that following the introduction of tobacco to <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medieval_India\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">medieval India</a> by the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jesuit\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Jesuits</a>, and since then tobacco use became widespread. The hookah or waterpipe was invented by Abu’l-Fath Gilani, a Persian physician of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Akbar\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Akbar</a>, in the Indian city of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fatehpur_Sikri\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Fatehpur Sikri</a> during <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mughal_India\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Mughal India</a>;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hookah#cite_note-Sivaramakrishnan4-5-10\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">[10]</a><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hookah#cite_note-Wealth-11\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">[11]</a> the hookah spread from the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_subcontinent\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Indian subcontinent</a> to Persia first, where the mechanism was modified to its current shape, and then to the Near East.<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hookah#cite_note-Aljarrah2009-12\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">[12]</a> Alternatively, it could have originated in the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Safavid_dynasty\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Safavid dynasty</a> of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Persia\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Persia</a>,<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hookah#cite_note-13\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">[13]</a><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hookah#cite_note-14\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">[14]</a> from where it eventually spread to the Indian subcontinent.</p>","url":"https://www.figma.com/community/file/993623434187891459"}
